{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:02:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:02:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15562"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15562"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.58,0.32,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61873"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8253"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"5776"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61873"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-month history of recurrent central chest pain. He has presented multiple times to this rural facility with similar symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a high school teacher and is active in his community. He is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis electrocardiogram shows normal sinus rhythm with no ischaemic changes. Blood tests including troponin, full blood count, and biochemistry are within normal limits on this occasion, as they had been previously. Recent transthoracic echocardiogram and computed tomography coronary angiogram are reported as normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest physiotherapy","Trial of proton pump inhibitor therapy","Referral for exercise stress test","Referral to cardiology outpatients","Referral for invasive coronary angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent chest pain that has been thoroughly investigated to exclude cardiac causes. When cardiac causes have been excluded, other common causes of chest pain should be considered, particularly gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD). Atypical presentations of GORD account for up to 60% of cases of non cardiac chest pain (NCCP). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrial of proton pump inhibitor therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. GORD is a common cause of non-cardiac chest pain, and a therapeutic trial can be both diagnostic and therapeutic. If symptoms improve with acid suppression, this supports a diagnosis of GORD. Doses should be adjusted to lowest effective level. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for invasive coronary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate given the normal CT coronary angiogram and absence of cardiac risk factors. Further cardiac investigation would be unlikely to yield new information, unless new symptoms consistent with cardiac chest pain occur. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for exercise stress test\u003C/strong\u003E would not add value to the diagnostic workup given the already normal CT coronary angiogram, which has a higher sensitivity and specificity for coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to cardiology outpatients\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary at this stage given the extensive cardiac workup has been negative. The focus should shift to investigating and treating other potential causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest physiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be an appropriate next step without features suggesting musculoskeletal pain such as reproducible chest wall tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther considerations in non-cardiac chest pain include oesophageal motility disorders, anxiety disorders, and musculoskeletal causes. If the proton pump inhibitor trial is unsuccessful, these alternatives should be explored with appropriate investigations and referrals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-cardiac chest pain often has an underlying gastrointestinal cause, particularly gastro-oesophageal reflux disease.","After excluding cardiac causes, empiric trial of proton pump inhibitor therapy is an appropriate initial management step.","Anxiety and stress can manifest as chest pain and should be considered in the differential diagnosis after excluding organic causes."],"references":["Saitta D, Hebbard G. Beyond the heart: Noncardiac chest pain. Aust J Gen Pract. 2022 Nov;51(11):849-854. doi: 10.31128/AJGP-06-22-6467. PMID: 36309997. Available online at ; https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/november/noncardiac-chest-pain"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T17:23:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T17:24:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8253"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61873"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":